sentence: Yūjirō Ishihara (石原 裕次郎, Ishihara Yūjirō, December 28, 1934 – July 17, 1987) was a Japanese actor and singer born in Kobe.
His elder brother is Shintaro Ishihara, an author, politician, and the Governor of Tokyo between 1999 and 2012.
His elder brother is Shintaro Ishihara, an author, politician, and the Governor of Tokyo between 1999 and 2012.
Yujiro's film debut was the 1956 film Season of the Sun, based on a novel written by his brother.
He was beloved by many fans as a representative youth star in the films of postwar Japan and subsequently as a macho movie hero.
Yūjirō grew up in Kobe, in Otaru, Hokkaidō, and in Zushi, Kanagawa.

He enrolled at Keio Shiki Boys' Senior High School, but in 1951 was admitted to Keio Senior High School.

However, in 1956, with help from producer Takiko Mizunoe and his brother Shintaro, he received a bit-part in the film adaptation of Shintaro's Akutagawa Prize-winning Season of the Sun, making his film debut.
Mie Kitahara, his co-star in a number of films beginning in 1956 with Crazed Fruit.
Yūjirō, together with Akira Kobayashi, was the main male star at Nikkatsu on Nikkatsu's move into the Roman Porno soft porn market.
However he was later diagnosed with liver cancer and died at Keio University Hospital in 1987 on July 17 at 4:26.
His final appearance as an actor was in the final episode of popular detective television drama Taiyō ni Hoero!.
Yujiro Ishihara was called a Japanese Elvis Presley and his films and music are still followed by lovers of the Shōwa period.
